<br>
Anywho...here's my question.<br>
<br>
Wouldn't elves have been the first blademasters if one thinks in a politically correct frame of mind?  Blademasters are*mean't*to be graceful fighters who hit pretty hard and swing fast.  Elves are supposedly a graceful and dextrous bunch.  During their time behind the veil the elves mostly honed themselves to be casting machines, but I doubt they would have been so narrow minded as to go without creating a military of some sort.  While the champ seems like the clear alternative, would you really think weak-wristed elves would be swinging around big hammers and swords?  Elves, being the graceful and lithe creatures they are, might utilize a weapon in each hand and attack quickly to make up for their innate lack of strength.  They'd hone their bodies into dextrous and quick beings, being able to evade and parry attacks to make up for their lack of constitution.  The only gap in my stupid li'l theory is the constant fluff about Blademasters being a bit rebellious in casting away all sense of magic in a strictly magical realm.  And it's common knowledge elves are a magical bunch.  Then I think up Triple-Wield.  I'm not to sure of the ethics of TW, but it seems to me like it is a sheer concentration of will directed at one's enemies.  Is that not magical?  Mentalists supposedly crush the minds of their assailants by will and a power over the mind.<br>
<br>
Does my idea have any merit?<br>
<br>
But then again, I'm an idiot...<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :| --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/indifferent.gif ALT=":|"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Peace,<br>
Joe<br>
