<br>
There was an episode of Highlander (the series) where Duncan was in Spain and he was learning a style of sword fighting. Each combatant had a thin sword (rapier?) in one hand and a thin dagger (dirk?) in the other. They fought inside a small square on the ground and it was more of a dance rather than a fight. The training square even had footprints on it rather like footprints that show a person how to dance. It was incredibly graceful and fluid. I don't think the weapons had edges so it was all pointwork. Strength didn't matter, you couldn't just bludgeon your opponent to death. You had to dance together, going through the different steps, attacking and countering, staying inside this rather small square, waiting for your opponent to make the wrong step. That's my image of the blademaster. Not the senseless rage of the berzerker, nor the efficiency of a merc completing a job however he can so he can get paid. The dance of a blademaster is death made beautiful.<br>
<br>
As you can tell, I've read a few too many cheesy fantasy books...<br>
